==English==

===Etymology===
Recorded since 1550, from {{etyl|frm}} [[plate-forme]], literally "flat form", from {{etyl|frm}} [[plate]] "flat" (from {{etyl|fro}} [[plat]], of uncertain origin) + [[forme]] "form" (from {{etyl|la}} [[forma]])

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-platform.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A raised [[stage]] from which [[speech]]es are made and on which musical and other [[performance]]s are made.
# {{politics}} A political [[stance]] on a broad set of issues, which are called [[plank]]s.
# A raised [[structure]] from which [[passenger]]s can [[enter]] or leave a train, metro etc.
# {{automobiles}} A set of [[component]]s [[share]]d by several [[vehicle]] models.
# {{computing}} A particular type of [[operating system]] or [[environment]] such as a [[database]] or other specific [[software]], and/or a particular type of [[computer]] or [[microprocessor]], used to describe a particular [[environment]] for running other software, or for defining a specific software or hardware environment for discussion purposes.
#: ''That program runs on an X-Window-System '''platform'''.
# A high [[shoe]] type with an extra layer between the inner- and outer soles

